d how their opponents attempted to silence them. He also reveals how monetary and political history unfolds in the tension between "moral economies of money" and "monetary silencing." Offering an introduction to money creation practices since the colonial era, the book enables readers to understand why most people are disconnected from knowledge about money creation today. At the same time, the book also allows readers to situate the recent prominence of Modern Monetary Theory (MMT) against a broader historical background. Historians of capitalism, economic and political sociologists, social theorists, anthropologists of money, and anyone seeking to understand monetary activism, will find this book helps to clarify present-day possibilities in light of historical processes.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 01. Dez 2022) 0aCurrency questionzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMonetary policyzUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMoneyxMoral and ethical aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 0aMoneyxPolitical aspectszUnited StatesxHistory. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Political Economy.2bisacsh  aUS history.  acredit.  adebt.  amonetary history.  amonetary theory.  amoral economy.  apublic finance.  asocial movements.  asociology of money.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertStanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022z978311076648640uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978150363345240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9781503633452423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9781503633452/original  a978-3-11-076648-6  Stanford University Press Complete eBook-Package 2022b2022  aGBV-deGruyter-alles